      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "Interpretation and approximate pH threshold:\n- Precipitation begins when the ion product [Ca^2+][C2O4^2−] exceeds Ksp. At 25 °C and I ≈ 0.1 M, Ksp ≈ 10^−7.86.\n- The fraction of total oxalate present as C2O4^2− rises sharply around the second acidity step (pKa ≈ 3.8 at 25 °C, I = 0.1 M), so the onset is closely tied to this pKa.\n- Without specific concentrations, the general criterion is α2(pH) ≈ Ksp / ([Ca]_total · [oxalate]_total), where α2 is the fraction of oxalate as C2O4^2−. Complexation (logβ1 ≈ 3.19 at I = 0) lowers the free-ion product and nudges the threshold pH upward.",
