      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "Worked example (to anchor “significant”):\n- If [Ca]_total = [oxalate]_total = 1 mM at 25 °C, I ≈ 0.1 M, ignoring CaC2O4(aq) complexation: you need α2 ≈ 10^−7.86 / (10^−3 × 10^−3) ≈ 0.014. That small fraction of C2O4^2− is reached already around pH ≈ 2–3, and precipitation strengthens rapidly as pH approaches and exceeds the second pKa (~3.8). Including CaC2O4(aq) complexation (β1 ≈ 10^3.19) reduces free ions and shifts onset upward somewhat, but the qualitative picture remains: “significant” precipitation typically emerges as pH moves into the vicinity of pKa2 and above.",
